post_text:
SPECIAL BOARD MEETING:
The SMUSD Governing Board will hold a Special Board Meeting on Friday, September 4th, at 10:00am regarding the reopening plan for District schools.

No action will be taken at this meeting. A video of the meeting will be available for later viewing on the District website.

We will provide a forum for community feedback on the presentation and reopening options. The Board will vote on a reopening plan and timeline at our Regular Board Meeting on September 15th.

The agenda and meeting access information will be available soon.

Public comments for the Special Board Meeting must be submitted electronically in advance at publiccomments@smusd.org by 8:00am on September 4th.

Dear SMUSD Colleagues, Parents, and Students,

As we launch our 138th academic school year, the COVID-19 era continues to be unlike any other we have experienced in our storied history. Together, we are forging ahead to ensure we support our students, each other, and our community. I express my sincerest appreciation for your flexibility and support as we welcome back our students and launch a new academic year via remote instruction. The success of each and every one of our students remains our true North Star! We, Team SMUSD, all 2400 strong, will continue to wrap our collective arms around our 21,000 students in a supportive and engaging virtual environment.

Click the link below to find important updates for the new academic school year.

https://www.smusd.org/news/what_s_new/welcome_back_-_2020_21_school_year

This week marked Classified School Employee Week! Our classified staff members play an important role in educating students. We can‚Äôt do it without them!

Thank you for the difference you make in the lives of our students, families, and district colleagues!

Certainly, the last 10 weeks have turned our world on its head and, yet, your commitment has shown through and through! To name a few: you have helped with the distribution of over 419,000 meals; have helped our sites and offices remain safe, cleaned, disinfected; have helped to prep and distribute thousands of chromebooks; and continue to assist in every department in our district--Instructional Services, Technology, Human Resources, Business Services, Facilities, and Maintenance & Operations!

post_text: Every year on #SchoolLunchHeroDay, we say thank you to the people who provide such an essential service to our students. Our Child Nutrition Services staff were some of the first to step up when the COVID-19 health crisis closed our schools. These heroes are outside most days, rain or shine, and now in the heat. They have produced and served over 303,299 meals (breakfast and lunch) since March 16 - and they do it with a smile, a wave, and a welcome. When they were called on during the pandemic to serve, they did - armed with masks and desire to help. Thank you to all of our CNS heroes, those working at school sites and those working behind the scenes. We appreciate you!!! SMUSD Child Nutrition Services

Dear SMUSD Community,

This week, we showcase our district‚Äôs AVID program. The AVID program serves more than 2 million students in over 7000 schools throughout the US. While its focus is college acceptance and college readiness, AVID also teaches students important life skills that include critical thinking, collaboration, time management, reflection, and self-advocacy, among many others. In the video, we highlight several students that embody the above traits.

Our district houses AVID programs at both the middle and high school level and every year we graduate AVID scholars that are ready to take on the challenges that await them in college and beyond.

Dear SMUSD Community,

Recently, two of our middle schools had the privilege of hosting Rose Schindler, Holocaust survivor and author of the book Two Who Survived, as part of the Anne Frank traveling exhibition. Rose shared her heartbreaking and devastating story of loss and survival with our students, parents, staff, and community. Her key messages included resilience, hope and ‚Äònever forgetting.‚Äô

Thank you to our student docents who did a wonderful job leading discussions throughout the exhibits as well as answering guest questions. Thank you also to our teachers and staff for helping to organize the traveling exhibit.

Please click on the following link to view this week‚Äôs message: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rHA2LVh1OHQ

Best,

Dr. Garc√≠a

post_text:
Woodland Park Middle School has been given the unique opportunity to host the traveling Anne Frank Museum Exhibit entitled ‚ÄúAnne Frank- A History for Today.‚Äù The exhibit will be displayed in the Performing Arts Center beginning February 10th through the 13th. WPMS is one of only six schools in all of San Diego County to host the exhibit and this will be the first time it comes to San Marcos. Several 8th grade students participated in a two-day docent training, led by the staff of the Anne Frank Museum, to learn about and develop a presentation on the exhibit to present back at WPMS. All SMUSD families and community members are invited to visit this exhibit on Wednesday, February 12th, from 4:00 p.m. to 7:00p.m. This is a free event and open to all! Rose Schindler, Holocaust survivor and author, just confirmed that she will be speaking at this event! Thank you to the Consulate of the Netherlands and the Anne Frank House in Amsterdam for this incredible opportunity!
Woodland Park Middle School PTO Woodland Park Middle

Update on the Novel Coronavirus on behalf of the County of San Diego Health and Human Services Agency (HHSA) Department of Public Health Services (PHS).

San Diego County has been selected to receive repatriated citizens from the Hubei province of China (city of Wuhan) arriving at Marine Corps Air Station (MCAS) Miramar. The federal government is the lead agency for this response, and the County of San Diego is working closely with these officials, the California Department of Public Health (CDPH), and regional public health jurisdictions on this rapidly evolving situation.

San Diego County residents can protect their health by taking preventive measures, such as frequent and proper hand washing, staying away from those who are ill, covering coughs and sneezes, and staying home if sick. It is not too late to get a flu shot to help prevent illness and symptoms similar to the novel (new) coronavirus.

For more information and preparedness activities regarding the Novel Coronavirus, please see attached letter from Dr. Wilma J. Wooten, Public Health Officer.

Update on the Novel Coronavirus on behalf of the County of San Diego Health and Human Services Agency (HHSA) Department of Public Health Services (PHS).

San Diego County has been selected to receive repatriated citizens from the Hubei province of China (city of Wuhan) arriving at Marine Corps Air Station (MCAS) Miramar. The federal government is the lead agency for this response, and the County of San Diego is working closely with these officials, the California Department of Public Health (CDPH), and regional public health jurisdictions on this rapidly evolving situation.

San Diego County residents can protect their health by taking preventive measures, such as frequent and proper hand washing, staying away from those who are ill, covering coughs and sneezes, and staying home if sick. It is not too late to get a flu shot to help prevent illness and symptoms similar to the novel (new) coronavirus.

For more information and preparedness activities regarding the Novel Coronavirus, please see attached letter from Dr. Wilma J. Wooten, Public Health Officer.
